{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_0144RzaDgsjpRdM3T8KyB521","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Story 8.1: Issue Tracker Module & CLI\n2\t\n3\tStatus: review\n4\t\n5\t<!-- Note: Validation is optional. Run validate-create-story for quality check before dev-story. -->\n6\t\n7\t## Story\n8\t\n9\tAs a developer,\n10\tI want to create, list, and manage issues via `codeharness issue`,\n11\tso that bugs and tech debt have a path to implementation alongside stories.\n12\t\n13\t## Acceptance Criteria\n14\t\n15\t1. **Given** no `.codeharness/issues.yaml` exists\n16\t   **When** `codeharness issue create \"Fix Docker timeout\" --priority high --source retro-sprint-1` runs\n17\t   **Then** `.codeharness/issues.yaml` is created with an `issues` array containing one entry with auto-generated `id` (format `issue-NNN`), `title`, `source`, `priority`, and `status: backlog`\n18\t   <!-- verification: runtime-provable -->\n19\t\n20\t2. **Given** `.codeharness/issues.yaml` already exists with issues\n21\t   **When** `codeharness issue create \"Another bug\" --priority medium` runs\n22\t   **Then** the new issue is appended to the existing `issues` array with the next sequential id\n23\t   **And** existing issues are not modified\n24\t   <!-- verification: runtime-provable -->\n25\t\n26\t3. **Given** `.codeharness/issues.yaml` exists with issues\n27\t   **When** `codeharness issue list` runs\n28\t   **Then** all issues are displayed with id, title, priority, status, and source\n29\t   **And** `--json` flag outputs JSON array format\n30\t   <!-- verification: runtime-provable -->\n31\t\n32\t4. **Given** `.codeharness/issues.yaml` exists with `issue-001` at status `backlog`\n33\t   **When** `codeharness issue close issue-001` runs\n34\t   **Then** `issue-001` status is updated to `done`\n35\t   **And** the file is written back with the updated status\n36\t   <!-- verification: runtime-provable -->\n37\t\n38\t5. **Given** issues use status values\n39\t   **When** any status is set (via create or close)\n40\t   **Then** the status value is one of: `backlog`, `ready`, `in-progress`, `review`, `verifying`, `done`, `failed`, `blocked` (same values as sprint-status.yaml)\n41\t   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n42\t\n43\t6. **Given** `codeharness issue create` is called without `--source`\n44\t   **When** the issue is created\n45\t   **Then** `source` defaults to `\"manual\"`\n46\t   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n47\t\n48\t7. **Given** `codeharness issue create` is called without `--priority`\n49\t   **When** the issue is created\n50\t   **Then** `priority` defaults to `\"medium\"`\n51\t   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n52\t\n53\t8. **Given** `codeharness issue close` is called with a non-existent issue id\n54\t   **When** the command executes\n55\t   **Then** it prints an error message and exits with code 1\n56\t   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n57\t\n58\t9. **Given** `codeharness issue list` is called when no `issues.yaml` exists\n59\t   **When** the command executes\n60\t   **Then** it prints \"No issues found\" and exits with code 0\n61\t   <!-- verification: runtime-provable -->\n62\t\n63\t10. **Given** `npm run build` is executed\n64\t    **When** the build completes\n65\t    **Then** it succeeds with zero errors\n66\t    **And** `npm run test:unit` passes with no regressions in existing test suites\n67\t    <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n68\t\n69\t11. **Given** unit tests for the issue tracker module and CLI\n70\t    **When** `npm run test:unit` is executed\n71\t    **Then** tests pass at 80%+ coverage for new code covering: issue creation, listing, closing, default values, error handling, file I/O, id generation\n72\t    <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n73\t\n74\t12. **Given** the workflow engine already reads `.codeharness/issues.yaml`\n75\t    **When** an issue is created via `codeharness issue create`\n76\t    **Then** the YAML format matches what `loadWorkItems()` in `workflow-engine.ts` expects: `issues` array with objects containing `id`, `title`, `source`, `priority`, `status`\n77\t    <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n78\t\n79\t## Tasks / Subtasks\n80\t\n81\t- [x] Task 1: Create `src/lib/issue-tracker.ts` — the issue tracker module (AC: #1, #2, #5, #6, #7, #12)\n82\t  - [x] Define `Issue` interface: `{ id: string; title: string; source: string; priority: string; status: string; created_at: string }`\n83\t  - [x] Define `IssuesFile` interface: `{ issues: Issue[] }`\n84\t  - [x] Implement `readIssues(dir?: string): IssuesFile` — reads `.codeharness/issues.yaml`, returns `{ issues: [] }` if missing\n85\t  - [x] Implement `writeIssues(data: IssuesFile, dir?: string): void` — writes to `.codeharness/issues.yaml`, creates `.codeharness/` if needed\n86\t  - [x] Implement `nextIssueId(existing: Issue[]): string` — generates `issue-NNN` with zero-padded 3-digit incrementing from highest existing id\n87\t  - [x] Implement `createIssue(title: string, options?: { priority?: string; source?: string }, dir?: string): Issue` — creates and persists a new issue\n88\t  - [x] Implement `closeIssue(id: string, dir?: string): Issue` — finds issue by id, sets status to `done`, writes back\n89\t  - [x] Define `VALID_STATUSES` constant matching sprint validator values: `backlog`, `ready`, `in-progress`, `review`, `verifying`, `done`, `failed`, `blocked`\n90\t  - [x] Define `VALID_PRIORITIES` constant: `low`, `medium`, `high`, `critical`\n91\t\n92\t- [x] Task 2: Create `src/commands/issue.ts` — the CLI command (AC: #1, #2, #3, #4, #8, #9)\n93\t  - [x] Register `issue` command with three subcommands: `create`, `list`, `close`\n94\t  - [x] `issue create <title>` with `--priority <p>` and `--source <s>` options\n95\t  - [x] `issue list` with `--json` support\n96\t  - [x] `issue close <id>` subcommand\n97\t  - [x] Use `ok()`, `fail()`, `info()`, `jsonOutput()` from `src/lib/output.ts`\n98\t  - [x] Export `registerIssueCommand` function\n99\t\n100\t- [x] Task 3: Register the command in `src/index.ts` (AC: #10)\n101\t  - [x] Import `registerIssueCommand` from `./commands/issue.js`\n102\t  - [x] Call `registerIssueCommand(program)` in the registration block\n103\t\n104\t- [x] Task 4: Write unit tests in `src/lib/__tests__/issue-tracker.test.ts` (AC: #10, #11)\n105\t  - [x] Test: `readIssues` returns empty array when file doesn't exist\n106\t  - [x] Test: `readIssues` parses existing issues.yaml correctly\n107\t  - [x] Test: `writeIssues` creates `.codeharness/` directory if needed\n108\t  - [x] Test: `writeIssues` outputs valid YAML matching workflow-engine expected format\n109\t  - [x] Test: `nextIssueId` generates `issue-001` for empty array\n110\t  - [x] Test: `nextIssueId` increments from highest existing id\n111\t  - [x] Test: `createIssue` sets defaults: source=`manual`, priority=`medium`, status=`backlog`\n112\t  - [x] Test: `createIssue` appends without modifying existing issues\n113\t  - [x] Test: `closeIssue` updates status to `done`\n114\t  - [x] Test: `closeIssue` throws for non-existent id\n115\t  - [x] Test: created YAML is compatible with `loadWorkItems()` expectations\n116\t\n117\t- [x] Task 5: Write command tests in `src/commands/__tests__/issue.test.ts` (AC: #10, #11)\n118\t  - [x] Test: `create` subcommand creates issues.yaml\n119\t  - [x] Test: `list` subcommand displays issues\n120\t  - [x] Test: `list` with `--json` outputs JSON\n121\t  - [x] Test: `list` with no issues prints \"No issues found\"\n122\t  - [x] Test: `close` subcommand updates status\n123\t  - [x] Test: `close` with bad id returns error\n124\t\n125\t- [x] Task 6: Verify build and all tests pass (AC: #10)\n126\t  - [x] Run `npm run build` — zero errors\n127\t  - [x] Run `npm run test:unit` — no regressions\n128\t\n129\t## Dev Notes\n130\t\n131\t### Architecture Context\n132\t\n133\tThe workflow engine (`src/lib/workflow-engine.ts`) already reads `.codeharness/issues.yaml` via `loadWorkItems()` (lines 186-222). It expects this YAML format:\n134\t\n135\t```yaml\n136\tissues:\n137\t  - id: issue-001\n138\t    title: Docker timeout handling too aggressive\n139\t    source: retro-sprint-1\n140\t    priority: high\n141\t    status: backlog\n142\t```\n143\t\n144\tThe engine filters issues with status `backlog` or `ready-for-dev` and creates `WorkItem` objects with `source: 'issues'`. This story builds the write side — the module and CLI that create/manage the file the engine already reads.\n145\t\n146\t### YAML Format Compatibility\n147\t\n148\tThe `loadWorkItems()` function expects:\n149\t- Top-level `issues` key containing an array\n150\t- Each issue has `id`, `title`, `source`, `priority`, `status` fields\n151\t- Status values `backlog` and `ready-for-dev` are the ones the engine picks up\n152\t\n153\tThe module MUST produce YAML that `loadWorkItems()` can parse. A compatibility test should round-trip: create issue → write YAML → parse with `yaml` library → verify structure matches what `loadWorkItems` expects.\n154\t\n155\t### Status Values\n156\t\n157\tFrom `src/modules/sprint/validator.ts`, the valid statuses are:\n158\t`backlog`, `ready`, `in-progress`, `review`, `verifying`, `done`, `failed`, `blocked`\n159\t\n160\tThe issue tracker must use the same set. Note: `ready-for-dev` appears in the workflow engine as a filter value but `ready` is the canonical status in the validator. Both should be accepted by the engine.\n161\t\n162\t### File Location\n163\t\n164\tPer architecture doc (AD6) and existing `run.ts` (line 159): `.codeharness/issues.yaml`. The path is already referenced in `run.ts`:\n165\t```typescript\n166\tissuesPath: join(projectDir, '.codeharness', 'issues.yaml'),\n167\t```\n168\t\n169\t### CLI Pattern\n170\t\n171\tFollow the existing command pattern:\n172\t- Export `registerIssueCommand(program: Command): void`\n173\t- Use Commander subcommands (`.command('create')`, `.command('list')`, `.command('close')`)\n174\t- Use `ok()`, `fail()`, `info()`, `jsonOutput()` from `src/lib/output.ts`\n175\t- Support `--json` global flag\n176\t- Set `process.exitCode = 1` on errors (do NOT call `process.exit()`)\n177\t\n178\t### ID Generation\n179\t\n180\tAuto-generated IDs follow `issue-NNN` format (zero-padded 3 digits). Parse existing IDs to find the max, increment by 1. If no issues exist, start at `issue-001`. If IDs are non-sequential (e.g., issue-001, issue-005), next is `issue-006`.\n181\t\n182\t### Dependencies\n183\t\n184\t- **New file:** `src/lib/issue-tracker.ts` — core module (~120-150 lines)\n185\t- **New file:** `src/commands/issue.ts` — CLI command (~100-120 lines)\n186\t- **New file:** `src/lib/__tests__/issue-tracker.test.ts` — module tests (~200-250 lines)\n187\t- **New file:** `src/commands/__tests__/issue.test.ts` — command tests (~150-180 lines)\n188\t- **Modified file:** `src/index.ts` — register new command (~2 lines)\n189\t- **No new npm dependencies** — uses `yaml` (already installed) and `commander` (already installed)\n190\t\n191\t### File Structure\n192\t\n193\t```\n194\tsrc/\n195\t  lib/\n196\t    issue-tracker.ts          (NEW)\n197\t    __tests__/\n198\t      issue-tracker.test.ts   (NEW)\n199\t  commands/\n200\t    issue.ts                  (NEW)\n201\t    __tests__/\n202\t      issue.test.ts           (NEW)\n203\t  index.ts                    (MODIFIED — add import + registration)\n204\t```\n205\t\n206\t### Testing Standards\n207\t\n208\t- Framework: `vitest` (already configured)\n209\t- Pattern: co-located tests in `__tests__/` directories\n210\t- Coverage target: 80%+\n211\t- Use `vi.mock` for fs operations in unit tests\n212\t- Use temp directories for integration-style tests (see existing patterns in `workflow-state.test.ts`)\n213\t\n214\t### Anti-Patterns to Avoid\n215\t\n216\t- **Do NOT use `process.exit()`** — set `process.exitCode` instead (existing pattern)\n217\t- **Do NOT use `any` in the API surface** — explicit TypeScript types per NFR18\n218\t- **Do NOT create a separate schema for issues.yaml** — the format is simple enough that runtime validation suffices\n219\t- **Do NOT modify `workflow-engine.ts`** — the read side already works; this story is write-only\n220\t- **Do NOT add beads or GitHub integration** — this is a standalone file-based tracker\n221\t\n222\t### Previous Story Intelligence\n223\t\n224\tFrom story 7-2 (resume after circuit breaker):\n225\t- The `run.ts` command already passes `issuesPath` to the workflow engine (line 159)\n226\t- The engine's `loadWorkItems()` already handles missing/malformed issues.yaml gracefully\n227\t\n228\tFrom architecture-v2.md (AD6):\n229\t- issues.yaml replaces beads as the lightweight issue tracker\n230\t- Same statuses, same execution path as stories\n231\t- Retro auto-import (story 8-2) will write to the same file\n232\t\n233\t### Git Intelligence\n234\t\n235\tRecent commits follow: `feat: story {key} — {description}`. This story creates new files (no modifications to existing code except index.ts registration). The codebase uses TypeScript with ESM `.js` extensions in import paths. Tests use vitest with vi.mock patterns.\n236\t\n237\t### References\n238\t\n239\t- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/epics-v2.md#Story 8.1: Issue Tracker Module & CLI]\n240\t- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/architecture-v2.md#AD6: Issue Tracking (Beads Replacement)]\n241\t- [Source: src/lib/workflow-engine.ts — loadWorkItems() (lines 136-226)]\n242\t- [Source: src/commands/run.ts — issuesPath (line 159)]\n243\t- [Source: src/modules/sprint/validator.ts — VALID_STATUSES (lines 12-21)]\n244\t- [Source: src/lib/output.ts — ok(), fail(), info(), jsonOutput()]\n245\t- [Source: src/index.ts — command registration pattern]\n246\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01CMZbq8RrvXCKSwd18t2Hto","session_id":"2800a04b-8151-4215-bf66-1f43973b9365","uuid":"96cbf600-09f4-4ab7-bd25-53913969f2db","timestamp":"2026-04-03T02:00:50.774Z"}
